{:proof/problem-id "apm-t96A08", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (refers explicitly to the manifold \\(M\\), the 1-form \\(\\omega\\), the path integral potential \\(f\\), and the exactness claim) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target asserts existence of \\(f\\) with \\(df=\\omega\\) under the path-independence hypothesis, not vice versa) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the statements stand alone as precise mathematical claims) · notes: helper lemma isolates part (a), main theorem combines both parts.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Show that a path-independent smooth 1-form has a smooth potential and is exact.\"\n :terms [{:name \"Path independence\"\n          :meaning \"Line integrals of ω depend only on endpoints.\"\n          :needed-because \"It ensures f(p)=∫_γ ω is well defined and allows differentiation under the integral sign.\"}\n         {:name \"Local coordinates\"\n          :meaning \"Choose charts so ω = Σ a_i dx^i with smooth a_i.\"\n          :needed-because \"Smoothness of f follows by differentiating coordinate expressions.\"}\n         {:name \"Exterior derivative\"\n          :meaning \"df is the 1-form determined by directional derivatives of f.\"\n          :needed-because \"Once df=ω, exactness is immediate.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"omega_path_independent_exact\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Define f by integrating ω from the base point, check smoothness in charts, then show df=ω.\"\n             :why-this-now \"This mirrors the textbook proof: well-defined potential + calculus ⇒ exactness.\"\n             :lean-target \"exact_of_path_independent_form\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Needs basic facts about smooth line integrals and exterior derivatives; Mathlib has smooth manifolds and differential forms but will require assembling existing lemmas.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"A smooth path-independent 1-form on a connected manifold equals df for the primitive defined by path integration.\"\n             :formal-name \"exact_of_path_independent_form\"\n             :formal-target \"Given a connected smooth manifold M and a smooth 1-form ω whose line integrals depend only on endpoints, there exists a smooth function f with df = ω.\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"This statement exactly matches parts (a) and (b).\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"exact_of_path_independent_form\"\n              :formal-statement \"∃ f : C^∞(M, ℝ), df = ω for the path-independent 1-form ω.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Combines `f` smooth and `ω` exact from Stage 1\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"smooth_potential_from_path_integral\"\n              :formal-statement \"The function f(p)=∫_{0→p} ω is smooth under the path-independence hypothesis.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Certifies part (a)\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** Manifold problems hide Euclidean intuition: “path independent ⇒ conservative” is familiar in ℝⁿ, but on a manifold there’s no canonical straight segment or coordinate primitive, so you must prove two things from scratch—(1) the potential \\(f(p)=\\int_{0\\to p}\\omega\\) is well defined and smooth, and (2) its exterior derivative is exactly \\(\\omega\\). Students often try to differentiate under the integral sign without checking that local definitions patch together smoothly.\n\n**Key insight.** Path independence lets you define \\(f\\) by integrating \\(\\omega\\) from the base point to \\(p\\). In a chart \\((U,x^1,\\dots,x^n)\\) you can homotope any path to the “coordinate broken line” inside \\(U\\), so on \\(U\\) the function \\(f\\) becomes an integral of a smooth expression \\(\\sum_i a_i(x)\\dot x^i\\). Differentiating this with respect to the endpoint recovers the coefficients \\(a_i\\), and hence \\(df = \\omega\\).\n\n**Complete proof.**\n\n1. **Well-defined potential.** Fix \\(0\\in M\\). For \\(p\\in M\\), let \\(f(p)=\\int_{0\\to p}\\omega\\) where the integral runs along any piecewise smooth path. The hypothesis ensures this value depends only on the endpoint.\n\n2. **Smoothness.** Take a chart \\((U,\\varphi)\\) with coordinates \\(x^1,\\dots,x^n\\) and write \\(\\omega=\\sum_i a_i(x)\\,dx^i\\) on \\(U\\). If \\(p\\in U\\) choose the path that first goes from \\(0\\) to some point \\(q\\in U\\) and then travels inside \\(U\\) along coordinate segments to \\(p\\). Path independence allows this choice. On \\(U\\) we thus get\n   \\[\n   f(p)=\\text{(constant depending on \\(q\\))} + \\int_0^1 \\sum_i a_i(x(t))\\,\\dot x^i(t)\\,dt\n   \\]\n   with \\(x(t)\\) a smooth path in \\(U\\) ending at \\(p\\). Differentiating \\(f\\circ\\varphi^{-1}\\) with respect to \\(x^j\\) pulls the derivative inside the integral, giving \\(\\partial (f\\circ\\varphi^{-1})/\\partial x^j = a_j\\circ\\varphi^{-1}\\). Because the \\(a_j\\) are smooth, so is \\(f\\). Iterating this argument shows \\(f\\in C^\\infty(M,\\mathbf R)\\).\n\n3. **Exactness.** Take \\(p\\in M\\) and \\(v\\in T_pM\\). Let \\(\\sigma\\) be a smooth curve with \\(\\sigma(0)=p\\), \\(\\sigma'(0)=v\\). By definition of \\(f\\),\n   \\[\n   (df)_p(v)=\\frac{d}{dt}\\Big|_{t=0}f(\\sigma(t))=\\frac{d}{dt}\\Big|_{t=0}\\int_{0\\to \\sigma(t)}\\omega = \\omega_p(v),\n   \\]\n   because the only part of the path that varies is the final short segment of \\(\\sigma\\), and the integral of \\(\\omega\\) over that short segment equals \\(\\omega_p(v)\\) to first order. Thus \\(df=\\omega\\), so \\(\\omega\\) is exact.\n\nTherefore \\(f\\) is smooth and \\(\\omega=df\\).\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.** Mathlib currently has smooth manifolds, cotangent bundles, and exterior derivatives but *not* line integrals of 1-forms over piecewise smooth curves or theorems differentiating such integrals. To formalize this proof we would need:\n\n1. A definition of \\(\\int_\\gamma \\omega\\) for a smooth 1-form \\(\\omega\\) and a curve \\(\\gamma\\colon I\\to M\\), together with the usual functorial properties.\n2. A local computation linking the integral-based \\(f\\) to the coefficients of \\(\\omega\\) in coordinates.\n3. A bridge between these coordinate derivatives and the intrinsic exterior derivative `df`.\n\nSince those APIs are missing, `apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T96A08/Apm_v2_t96A08_1775012559877/Main.lean` currently just records a TODO comment, and `lake build …Main` succeeds trivially. Once Mathlib gains line-integral support, we can translate the Stage 1 argument directly: define `f`, prove its smoothness chartwise, and then show `df = ω`.\n\n**What connects.** This is the standard “line integral depends only on endpoints ⇔ form is exact” fact from vector calculus, generalized to manifolds. The technique appears whenever you certify that a closed form is exact by integrating from a base point, e.g. in proving Poincaré’s lemma on star-shaped sets, recognizing conservative force fields in physics, or showing that the circulation of an irrotational fluid vanishes. On exam day, remember: path independence gives you a global potential, and differentiating the potential reproduces the form.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph [{:lemma "unparsed-lemma", :formal-dependency "1. **Well-defined potential.** Fix \\(0\\in M\\). For \\(p\\in M\\), let \\(f(p)=\\int_{0\\to p}\\omega\\) where the integral runs along any piecewise smooth path. The hypothesis ensures this value depends only on the endpoint.", :informal-dependency nil, :why-this-now nil, :lean-type "1. **Well-defined potential.** Fix \\(0\\in M\\). For \\(p\\in M\\), let \\(f(p)